    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1987-04-30T22:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1987-04-26T23:00:00-05:00" n="361"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d361">
                <head>361. Paper Prepared in the National Security Council<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d361fn1">Source: Reagan Library, Bledsoe, Ralph: Files,
                        330—Stratospheric Ozone (1985 to June 1987) [7]. No classification marking.
                        In the top margin, an unknown hand wrote: “Wed 2:00 5806 Climate Friday 1:00
                        p.m. <hi rend="italic">Thursday 3:30 pm.</hi>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJR_3">JR Spradley</persName>’s proposal.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1987-04-27T00:00:00-04:00" to="1987-04-30T23:59:59-04:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">U.S. Negotiating Strategy for <gloss target="#t_UNEP_1"
                        >UNEP</gloss> Ozone Protocol Negotiations Third Session: April 27–30,
                    Geneva</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">
                    <hi rend="roman">I.</hi> Controls</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">A. First Step</p>
                <p>1. Freeze “emissions” at 1986 levels.</p>
                <p>• include all CFCs and Halons</p>
                <p>• automatic 0–2 years after entry into force</p>
                <p>2. 20% Reduction</p>
                <p>• include <gloss target="#t_CFC_1">CFC</gloss> 11, 12, 113</p>
                <p>• automatic 2–4 years after entry into force</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">B. Second Step</p>
                <p>• “up to” 50% reduction, subject to science<note n="2" xml:id="d361fn2">An
                        unknown hand highlighted this phrase and wrote: “and other tech &amp;
                        compliance info? (i.e. substit’s &amp; <gloss target="#t_LDC_1"
                        >LDC</gloss>’s.).”</note>
                </p>
                <p>• include <gloss target="#t_CFC_1">CFC</gloss> 11, 12, 113</p>
                <p>• within 8–10 years after entry into force</p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">C. Third Step</p>
                <p>• “up to” 95% reduction, subject to science</p>
                <p>• include <gloss target="#t_CFC_1">CFC</gloss> 11, 12, 113</p>
                <p>• within 14–16 years after entry into force</p>
                <pb facs="1077" n="1031" xml:id="pg_1031"/>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">
                    <hi rend="roman">II.</hi> General Provisions</p>
                <p>• <hi rend="italic">Emissions.</hi> Define “emissions” as weighted “adjusted
                    production” (P+I–E–D) (but consider other alternatives)</p>
                <p>• <hi rend="italic">Country Coverage.</hi> All major producing/using countries
                    must sign; encourage potential major producers/users (e.g., China, India) to
                    sign; allow (?) <gloss target="#t_LDC_1">LDC</gloss>’s to join (but not if they
                    get an emissions allowance)</p>
                <p>• <hi rend="italic">Scientific Assessment.</hi> Next major review 4–6 years after
                    entry into force, then every 6 years thereafter; minor reviews every 2 years
                    (also include technical and economic assessments)</p>
                <p>• <hi rend="italic">Trade Aspects.</hi> Support provisions to encourage
                    compliance with controls.</p>
            </div>
